1️⃣ Core Teaching (Simple, Exam-Oriented)
🔹 What is a High Court?

A High Court is the highest judicial authority at the state level.

Each state has a High Court
Some High Courts serve multiple states/UTs

📌 Mentioned in Articles 214–231

🔵 Composition
Chief Justice of High Court
Other judges (decided by President)
🔹 Appointment of Judges
Appointed by President
Consultation with:
Chief Justice of India
Governor of State
Chief Justice of High Court

📌 Collegium system followed.

🔴 Qualifications
Citizen of India
Advocate for 10 years OR
Judicial office for 10 years
🔹 Tenure
Retires at 62 years

📌 Difference from Supreme Court (65 years)

🔹 Jurisdiction of High Court
1️⃣ Original Jurisdiction
Civil & criminal cases
2️⃣ Appellate Jurisdiction
Appeals from lower courts
3️⃣ Writ Jurisdiction (Article 226)

Can issue writs for:

Fundamental Rights
Other legal rights

📌 Wider than Supreme Court.

4️⃣ Supervisory Jurisdiction
Controls lower courts
Ensures proper functioning
🔹 Independence of High Court
Removal by impeachment
Security of tenure
Salary protection
🔹 Key Difference (SC vs HC)
Feature	Supreme Court	High Court
Level	National	State
Retirement	65	62
Writ power	FR only	FR + legal rights
